{
  "meta": {
    "id": "goh_orion_institution_aiwhatif_v1",
    "title": "Global Occupational Health Institution — AIWhatif Parameter Lab",
    "subtitle": "A Monte Carlo proxy simulator of the PetraNex/Orion Goguen institution. Adjust institutional parameters to explore how jurisdictional divergence, profitability pressure, contractor assurance, culture, surveillance, and governance affect satisfaction, coherence, harm prevention, and assurance outcomes.",
    "footerNote": "This simulator is a formalized proxy model derived from the Goguen-institution representation of the Orion occupational health scenario. It is for exploratory reasoning only; it does not replace legal advice, industrial hygiene assessment, occupational medicine judgment, or operational risk review."
  },
  "project": {
    "name": "PetraNex Orion Global Occupational Health Institution",
    "description": "A many-sorted institutional proxy model for a multinational oil-and-gas occupational-health system spanning multiple jurisdictions, contractor chains, exposure hazards, cultural conditions, and reporting regimes.",
    "promptTemplate": {
      "title": "AI Prompt Generator",
      "instructions": "Generate a structured prompt for analysing the occupational-health institution under the chosen slider settings.",
      "defaultAssumptions": "Assume the Orion business unit spans offshore, terminal, vessel, and fabrication-yard operations; key hazards are noise, isocyanates, MSDs, and psychosocial strain; corporate minima are enforced through OneHealth; and Monte Carlo outputs are interpreted as proxy probabilities rather than empirical forecasts.",
      "promptText": [
        "You are analysing a Goguen-style occupational-health institution for a global oil-and-gas enterprise.",
        "",
        "Use the following current parameter settings as the model inputs:",
        "{{PARAMETERS_LIST}}",
        "",
        "Interpret the institution as having signatures for jurisdictions, sites, employers, workers, hazards, controls, surveillance, reports, cultural dimensions, actions, and time; sentences representing corporate minima and local/legal constraints; models representing sampled operational states; and satisfaction as whether the sampled state meets the key occupational-health governance clauses.",
        "",
        "Your task:",
        "1) Explain how the chosen slider values change the likely satisfaction of the institutional sentences on hazard identification, exposure baselines, surveillance, contractor equivalence, worker participation, professional independence, psychosocial review, and balanced reporting.",
        "2) Identify which tensions dominate in this configuration: jurisdictional divergence, profitability pressure, transactional reporting, contractor gaps, cultural incoherence, or weak remediation.",
        "3) Explain the expected effects on the main Monte Carlo outputs: institution satisfaction, cross-jurisdiction coherence, preventable harm avoidance, and assurance/continuity.",
        "4) Give concrete examples tied to the Orion scenario: Platform Delta noise, contractor isocyanate exposure in yards, crane-maintenance MSD risk, and vessel psychosocial strain.",
        "5) Recommend the smallest set of interventions that would most improve satisfaction under the current settings.",
        "6) Be explicit about uncertainty, hidden assumptions, and what evidence would most reduce uncertainty.",
        "",
        "Project refinements supplied by the user (incorporate carefully; if empty, state assumptions you made):",
        "{{REFINEMENTS}}"
      ]
    }
  },
